    "pathophysiology": "Direct mechanical trauma to RBCs occurs when they pass through high-shear stress environments. In prosthetic valve hemolysis, RBCs are sheared by turbulent flow around the valve apparatus, especially with paravalvular leaks. In march hemoglobinuria, repetitive impact on the soles during running/drumming causes capillary trauma and RBC fragmentation in the feet. The fragmented RBCs undergo intravascular hemolysis, releasing hemoglobin into plasma. Free hemoglobin binds haptoglobin (consuming it) and is filtered by the kidneys, causing hemoglobinuria. Chronic urinary iron loss leads to iron deficiency anemia, compounding the hemolytic anemia.",
